The '''Integrated Floating Cage Aquageoponics System (IFCAS)''' was developed as an [[aquaculture]]-horticulture based on the concept of [[integrated farming]] system approach firstly in [[Bangladesh]] in 2013 to produce fish and vegetables in floating condition where waste materials (fish [[feces]] and unused [[Animal feed|feed]]) from fish culture dissolved in the pond water and settled on the bottom mud are used for vegetables production.<ref>{{cite journal | last1 = Haque | display-authors = etal   | year = 2015 | title = Integrated floating cage aquageoponics system (IFCAS): An innovation in fish and vegetable production for shaded ponds in Bangladesh | url = http://www.sciencedirect.com/science/article/pii/S2352513415000125 | journal = Aquaculture Reports| volume = 2| issue = | pages = 1–9| doi=10.1016/j.aqrep.2015.04.002}}</ref><ref>Ariful Islam. "ছায়াযুক্ত পুকুরে মাছ ও সবজির সমন্বিত চাষের টেকসই প্রযুক্তি 'ইফকাস'" {{cite web|url=http://www.dailynayadiganta.com/details.php?nayadiganta%3DNDA5NDQ%3D%26s%3DMTY%3D |title=Archived copy |accessdate=16 September 2014 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140525210850/http://www.dailynayadiganta.com/details.php?nayadiganta=NDA5NDQ%3D&s=MTY%3D |archivedate=25 May 2014 |df=dmy-all }}  Newspaper Popular Article, 25 May 2014</ref> Of the newly adopted term ''aquageoponics'', [[wikt:aqua|aqua]], [[wikt:geo|geo]] and [[ponics]]<ref>Aquaponics (fish and gardening)http://supurbanfarm.wordpress.com/aquaponics/</ref> means water, mud/[[soil]] and [[Horticulture|cultivation]], respectively. In fact, aquageoponics is a new version of traditional aquaponics where soil is used as a medium instead of conventional media such as hydroton, [[pebble]]s, and sponges.

== Development process of IFCAS ==

Filling the gap of supply and demand of fish and vegetables for improving household nutrition, the ANEP ([[Agriculture and Nutrition Extension Project]])<ref>ANEP, http://www.ide-uk.org/wp-content/uploads/2013/02/OS0526_ANE-Project-Summary.pdf</ref> funded by the [[European Union]] (EU) works in [[Barisal District]] of [[Bangladesh]] following an integrated aquaculture-agriculture approach.<ref>Md. Yusuf Ali. "ইফকাস পদ্ধতিতে পুকুরে মাছ ও সবজি চাষ" {{cite web|url=http://www.alokitobangladesh.com/agri-&-firmar/2014/05/08/71084 |title=Archived copy |accessdate=16 September 2014 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140916062133/http://www.alokitobangladesh.com/agri-%26-firmar/2014/05/08/71084 |archivedate=16 September 2014 |df=dmy-all }}  Newspaper Article, 8 May 2014</ref> Pond [[Levee|dykes]] in Barisal are commonly used for planting trees by the rural people which provide cooking [[fuel]], fruits, and timber for sale. Trees on the pond dyke create [[shadow]], which reduce [[sunlight]] penetration to the edges of the pond and the dykes. In this context, IFCAS was developed in the shaded ponds without changing the vegetative nature of pond dykes following the collegial principles of action research. In the whole process of action research, farmers, researchers and developers from [[Bangladesh Agricultural University]] (BAU), [[Mymensingh]], [[Patuakhali Science and Technology University]], Bangladesh, WorldFish-ANEP, and [[Bangladesh Fisheries Research Forum]] (BFRF)<ref>Bangladesh Fisheries Research Forum (BFRF)http://bfrf.org/</ref> together were involved in the trial of this technology. The concept of IFCAS was developed by Dr. M. Mahfujul Haque (Ripon), Professor, Department of Aquaculture, BAU, Mymensingh who led the action research as the Principal Investigator.<ref>Md. Yusuf Ali. "মাছ ও সবজির সমন্বিত চাষ ইফকাস"  http://www.jjdin.com/?view=details&archiev=yes&arch_date=1 June 2014&type=single&pub_no=852&cat_id=1&menu_id=68&news_type_id=1&index=0  Newspaper Article, 1 June 2014</ref><ref>WorldFish, 2015. Aquaculture without borders: Most significant change stories from the Agriculture and Nutrition Extension Project in Bangladesh and Nepal. http://pubs.iclarm.net/resource_centre/2015-03.pdf</ref>

== Technical aspects ==

A 9 m<sup>2</sup> rectangular iron-bar made structure was constructed, having four [[wikt:Special:Search/concave|concave]] grooves in its four [[wikt:corner|corner]]s for holding floats of plastic drums. The whole bottom of the structure was surrounded by a rectangular nylon [[net (device)|net]] [[cage (enclosure)|cage]] with the dimensions of length-3.66 m × width-2.44 m × depth-1.25 m. Under the four corners and middle points of the net, half-brick weights were hung to ensure that the net retained a rectangular structure under the water. In the middle of both widths of IFCAS, two pits filled with dried pond mud of the same pond are used as medium for vegetable [[plantation]]. On the top of the structure, a [[scaffold]] was made using split [[bamboo]] and net for vegetables to [[tendril|climb on]].<ref>IFCAS (Integrated Floating Cage Aquageoponics System) in Bangladesh and Nepal https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=LzA05QfZYCs YouTube Video, Access on 16 September 2014</ref>

== Benefits ==

Compared to other [[aquaculture]] technology, IFCAS showed several benefits to the adopting farmers. Like traditional [[aquaponics]], fish and plants also rely on each other in aquageoponics.<ref>{{cite web|title=Continuing Education|url=https://www.ufv.ca/continuing_studies/courses/trades-and-technology/agriculture-and-horticulture/|accessdate=29 September 2014}}</ref> Here a mutual relationship exists between fish and plants. Unused fish feed and excrements result in nitrogenous wastes in the pond water and mud what are used as nutrients (nitrate) by the plants in IFCAS. Here some substrates such as, fallen leaves from horticulture plants, mud and materials in IFCAS (such as drums, iron plates etc.) harbour the nitrifying bacteria what convert toxic [[ammonia]] to less harmful [[nitrate]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Aquaponics |url=http://www.growingpower.org/aquaponics.htm |accessdate=29 September 2014 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140717053427/http://www.growingpower.org/aquaponics.htm |archivedate=17 July 2014 }}</ref> Plant roots hanging from IFCAS pits, absorb [[nutrients]] more effectively from water than plants do in traditional [[soil]] based agriculture as roots are longer and healthier in IFCAS. Like in aquaponics, plants grow faster in IFCAS also. Moreover, symbiotically plants facilitate by providing fish with ammonia free water in return.<ref>{{cite web|title=Aquaponics Supplies|url=http://aquaponicssuppliescom.wordpress.com/2013/03/05/aquaponic-gardening-design-pdf-ebook/|accessdate=29 September 2014}}</ref> Harvesting fish and vegetables from IFCAS is very easy for both men and women. Apart from consumption of fish and vegetables at the household level, farmers earned money by selling fish from IFCAS. IFCAS is not only useful in the small shaded ponds but also in multi-ownership ponds, state-owned ponds, natural water bodies (beel), rivers, canals, and the waterlogged areas affected by climate change. Along with dissemination of this technology in Bangladesh, IFCAS has been trialed in ponds in [[Nepal]] which was found encouraging for nursing [[Juvenile fish|fish fingerlings]] and vegetables during [[dry season]].<ref>WorldFish. "Floating gardens can feed Bangladesh"   Article, http://www.worldfishcenter.org/featured/floating-gardens-can-feed-bangladesh 11 October 2013</ref>

==Stocking density and production==
Professor Dr. M. Mahfujul Haque, the leading researcher of the IFCAS project, recommends a stocking density for monosex [[Tilapia]] of 100 fry per cubic meter. For vegetables, [[cucumber]], [[bean]], [[bitter melon]], Asian spinach etc. are recommended. Tilapia production of 31&nbsp;kg and 52&nbsp;kg per 9 m<sup>2</sup> were found within 120 days of period in the IFCAS placed heavily shaded and moderately-shaded ponds, respectively.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Mohammad|first1=Ali|title=(Integrated Culture of Fish and Vegetables)মাছ ও সবজির সমন্বিত চাষ ইফকাস|url=http://www.jjdin.com/?view=details&archiev=yes&arch_date=01-06-2014&type=single&pub_no=852&cat_id=1&menu_id=68&news_type_id=1&index=0|accessdate=29 September 2014}}</ref> On-station and farmer participatory on-farm research works are underway focusing suitable fish species combination in the cage of IFCAS to determine its optimum productivity potential.

