{{Infobox medical condition (new) | name = Radiation-induced lung injury | synonyms = | image = Radiation pneumonitis (4863802675).jpg | caption = Radiation pneumonitis | pronounce = | field = | symptoms = | complications = | onset = | duration = | types = | causes = | risks = | diagnosis = | differential = | prevention = | treatment = | medication = | prognosis = | frequency = | deaths = }} '''Radiation-induced lung injury''' is a general term for damage to the [[lung]]s which occurs as a result of exposure to [[ionizing radiation]].<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Marks|first=Lawrence B.|last2=Yu|first2=Xiaoli|last3=Vujaskovic|first3=Zjelko|last4=Small|first4=William|last5=Folz|first5=Rodney|last6=Anscher|first6=Mitchell S.|date=July 2003|title=Radiation-induced lung injury|journal=Seminars in Radiation Oncology|volume=13|issue=3|pages=333–345|doi=10.1016/S1053-4296(03)00034-1|issn=1053-4296|pmid=12903021}}{{Subscription or libraries|sentence|via=[[ScienceDirect]]}}</ref> In general terms, such damage is divided into early [[Inflammation|inflammatory]] damage (''radiation pneumonitis'') and later complications of chronic [[scarring]] (''radiation fibrosis''). Pulmonary radiation injury most commonly occurs as a result of [[radiation therapy]] administered to treat [[cancer]].{{citation needed|date=November 2017}}
==Symptoms and signs== The [[lung]]s are a radiosensitive organ, and radiation [[pneumonitis]] can occur leading to [[pulmonary insufficiency]] and death (100% after exposure to 50 gray of radiation), in a few months. Radiation [[pneumonitis]] is characterized by: *Loss of [[epithelial cell]]s *[[Pulmonary edema|Edema]] *[[Inflammation]] *Occlusions airways, air sacs and blood vessels *[[Fibrosis]]
